                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Memory efficient</strong> — only one object allocated for shared concerns</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Lazy initialisation</strong> — created only when first needed</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Persistence</strong> — state survives across component lifecycles</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Simple API</strong> — <code>getInstance()</code> is easy to understand</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Coordination</strong> — ideal for cross-cutting concerns like logging or config</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="cons-card">
                    <h3>❌ Cons</h3>
                    <ul class="point-list">
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Hidden coupling</strong> — consumers depend on a global, not an abstraction</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Hard to test</strong> — shared state bleeds between unit tests</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Concurrency risk</strong> — race conditions in multi-threaded environments</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Violates SRP</strong> — manages both its own creation and its behaviour</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Tight lifecycle</strong> — lives for the entire app lifetime by default</li>
                        <li><span class="point-icon">→</span> <strong>Subclassing issues</strong> — extending a singleton is non-trivial</li>
                    </ul>
