        <!-- SECTION 7: DI COMPARISON -->
        <section>
            <div class="section-header">
                <div class="section-label">▣ Alternative Approach</div>
                <h2>When Dependency Injection Is Better</h2>
                <p>DI passes dependencies explicitly rather than pulling them from a global.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="di-section">
                <h3>💉 Dependency Injection Overview</h3>
                <p>
                    Instead of calling <code>ThemeManager.getInstance()</code> inside a component,
                    Dependency Injection <em>passes</em> the theme service into the component from
                    the outside — via a constructor, a function parameter, or a framework container.
                    This makes dependencies explicit, swappable, and mockable.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> reach for a Singleton when you genuinely need
                    one shared instance (config, logger, cache). Reach for DI when you need
                    flexibility, testability, or multiple environments.
                </p>
                <div class="di-scenarios">
                    <div class="di-scenario">
                        <h4>🧪 Unit Testing</h4>
                        <p>Inject a mock ThemeService instead of the real singleton — no global state pollution between tests.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="di-scenario">
                        <h4>🌍 Multi-tenant Apps</h4>
                        <p>Each tenant gets their own ThemeService instance injected — impossible with a true singleton.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="di-scenario">
                        <h4>🔄 Hot-swapping</h4>
                        <p>Replace the theme implementation at runtime (e.g. A/B test) without touching consumers.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="di-scenario">
                        <h4>🖥️ SSR / Node.js</h4>
                        <p>Server-side rendering needs per-request isolation — a global singleton would leak state between requests.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="di-scenario">
                        <h4>📦 Library Code</h4>
                        <p>Libraries should never impose a singleton on consumers — pass the service

