    <section id="discussion">
      <div class="discussion">
        <h2>📚 Discussion: The Singleton Pattern</h2>
        <p class="subtitle">
          An honest look at when the singleton shines, when it hurts, and what
          to reach for instead.
        </p>

        <!-- Pros / Cons -->
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-cons-box pros-box">
            <h3>✅ Advantages</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Guarantees a single instance, preventing inconsistent duplicated state (e.g. two conflicting theme values).</li>
              <li>Globally accessible without prop-drilling or context providers — any module can call <code>getInstance()</code>.</li>
              <li>Lazy instantiation means no cost is paid until the instance is first needed.</li>
              <li>Minimal boilerplate compared to full dependency-injection containers.</li>
              <li>Naturally centralises related logic (storage, OS preference detection, observer notification) in one place.</li>
              <li>Easy to reason about for small, focused concerns like UI theming or logging.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="pros-cons-box cons-box">
            <h3>✗ Disadvantages</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Introduces <strong>hidden global state</strong> — callers are implicitly coupled to a concrete class, not an interface.</li>
              <li>Makes <strong>unit testing hard</strong>: you cannot inject a mock or reset the instance between test runs without workarounds.</li>
              <li>Violates the <strong>Single Responsibility Principle</strong> by also managing its own lifecycle.</li>
              <li>In multi-threaded environments (e.g. Node.js workers) naive implementations can create multiple instances.</li>
              <li>Encourages <strong>tight coupling</strong> — refactoring away from a singleton later is painful.</li>
              <li>Lifetime is tied to the application, which can cause <strong>memory leaks</strong> if it holds large references.</li>
              <li>Difficult to subclass or extend without modifying the original class.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Alternatives -->
        <div class="alt-box">
          <h3>🔀 When to prefer Dependency Injection or other patterns</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Large, testable applications:</strong> use a DI container (e.g. InversifyJS, Angular's injector, Spring).
              Consumers declare what they need via interfaces; the container wires concrete implementations — swapping a mock
              in tests requires zero changes to production code.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>React / Vue / Svelte apps:</strong> use a <strong>Context / provide-inject</strong> mechanism.
              The framework manages the lifetime and scope of the shared value; components subscribe declaratively and
              re-render reactively without touching a global variable.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Reactive state (Redux, Zustand, Pinia, MobX):</strong> these libraries give you a single store
              (similar intent to a singleton) but with explicit actions, immutable updates, devtools and time-travel
              debugging — far better observability than a hand-rolled singleton.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>ES Modules as singletons:</strong> a plain JS module that exports a frozen object or a set of
              functions is effectively a singleton — the module cache guarantees one instance — without any class
              boilerplate. This is the idiomatic modern JavaScript approach.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Service Locator pattern:</strong> a registry that maps abstract keys to concrete implementations.
              More flexible than a singleton (implementations can be swapped at runtime) but still carries global-state
              concerns; use with caution.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Observer / Event Bus:</strong> if multiple parts of the app need to <em>react</em> to theme
              changes rather than <em>read</em> the theme, an event bus decouples producers from consumers entirely —
              neither side needs a reference to the other.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Verdict -->
        <div class="verdict">
          <h3>⚖️ Verdict for this demo</h3>
          <p>
            For a <strong>simple, client-side UI preference</strong> like dark/light theming, the singleton is a
            pragmatic and entirely reasonable choice. The state is genuinely global (the whole page shares one theme),
            there is exactly one logical instance, and the cost of a full DI framework would far outweigh the benefit.
            However, if this were part of a <strong>large React application</strong>, the idiomatic solution would be
            a <code>ThemeContext</code> with a custom hook, or a lightweight state library — giving you the same
            single-source-of-truth guarantee with reactivity, server-side rendering support, and easy testability
            built in. The singleton pattern is not inherently bad; it is a tool best applied to <em>genuinely global,
            single-instance concerns</em> in <em>small-to-medium scopes</em> where testability is not a primary
            constraint.
          </p>
        </div>
