  <!-- ── Pros & Cons Section ── -->
  <section id="proscons">
    <div class="container">
      <h4>Analysis</h4>
      <h2>Singleton: Pros, Cons &amp; When to Use It</h2>
      <p>The Singleton pattern is one of the most recognised — and most debated — patterns in software design. Here is an honest assessment.</p>

      <div class="pros-cons-grid">
        <div class="pros-box">
          <h3>✅ Advantages</h3>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Single source of truth</strong> — state is never duplicated or out of sync across components.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Controlled access</strong> — one well-defined point to read or mutate shared state.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Lazy initialisation</strong> — the instance is only created when first needed, saving resources.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Global accessibility</strong> — any module can call <code>getInstance()</code> without prop-drilling.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Low overhead</strong> — no dependency injection framework or context API needed for simple cases.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Predictable</strong> — behaviour is easy to reason about for truly global concerns like theme or locale.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="cons-box">
          <h3>❌ Disadvantages</h3>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Global mutable state</strong> — any code anywhere can change the singleton, making bugs hard to trace.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Tight coupling</strong> — consumers are directly coupled to the concrete class, not an abstraction.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Hard to test</strong> — you cannot easily swap the singleton for a mock; tests share state and can bleed into each other.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Hidden dependencies</strong> — callers do not declare what they depend on, violating explicit dependency principles.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Concurrency issues</strong> — in multi-threaded environments (e.g., Node.js worker threads) naive singletons can race.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span><strong>Violates SRP</strong> — the class manages both its own logic <em>and</em> its own lifecycle.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alt-box">
          <h3>🔵 When It Is Appropriate</h3>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span>Truly global, app-wide settings: <strong>theme, locale, feature flags</strong>.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span>Expensive-to-create resources: <strong>database connection pools, loggers, caches</strong>.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span>Hardware or OS resources where only one instance makes sense: <strong>clipboard, GPU context</strong>.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span>Small scripts or prototypes where DI overhead is not justified.</span></li>
            <li><span class="bullet">→</span> <span>When the singleton is <strong>read-heavy and rarely mutated</strong>.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <blockquote>
        <p>"The Singleton pattern is like a global variable with a fancy name. Use it only when you truly need one and only one instance, and when the cost of that global coupling is lower than the benefit of guaranteed uniqueness."</p>
        <cite>— Paraphrased from <em>Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software</em>, Gang of Four</cite>
      </blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Alternatives Section ── -->
  <section id="alternatives">
    <div class="container">
      <h4>Better Approaches</h4>
      <h2>When Dependency Injection Is Superior</h2>
      <p>Dependency Injection (DI) inverts control: instead of a component reaching out to grab a singleton, the dependency is <em>provided to it</em>. This makes code more testable, flexible, and honest about its dependencies.</p>

      <div class="alert alert-info">
        <span class="alert-icon">ℹ️</span>
        <span><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> If you find yourself writing <code>ThemeManager.getInstance()</code> inside a unit-testable function, consider injecting the manager as a parameter instead.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-icon">💉</div>
          <h3>Constructor Injection</h3>
          <p>Pass the dependency through the constructor. The consumer declares exactly what it needs, making dependencies explicit and mockable.</p>
          <pre><code><span class="code-comment">// ✅ Explicit, testable</span>
<span class="code-keyword">class</span> <span class="code-fn">Header</span> {
  <span class="code-fn">constructor</span>(<span class="code-var">themeService</span>) {
    <span class="code-keyword">this</span>.theme = themeService;
  }
}
<span class="code-comment">// Test: inject a mock</span>
<span class="code-keyword">new</span> <span class="code-fn">Header</span>(mockTheme);</code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-icon">⚛️</div>
          <h3>React Context / Provider</h3>
          <p>React's Context API is DI built into the framework. A Provider wraps the tree; consumers read from it without coupling to a concrete class.</p>
          <pre><code><span class="code-keyword">const</span> ThemeCtx = createContext();

<span class="code-comment">// Provider owns the state</span>
<span class="code-fn">ThemeProvider</span> = ({ children }) => {
  <span class="code-keyword">const</span> [theme, setTheme] = useState(<span class="code-string">'light'</span>);
  <span class="code-keyword">return</span> (
    &lt;ThemeCtx.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}&gt;
      {children}
    &lt;/ThemeCtx.Provider&gt;
  );
};</code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-icon">🏪</div>
          <h3>Centralised Store (Redux / Zustand)</h3>
          <p>A store is conceptually a singleton but with strict conventions — actions, reducers, and selectors — making state changes traceable and time-travel debuggable.</p>
          <pre><code><span class="code-comment">// Zustand — DI-friendly store</span>
<span class="code-keyword">const</span> useTheme = <span class="code-fn">create</span>(set => ({
  theme: <span class="code-string">'light'</span>,
  toggle: () => set(s => ({
    theme: s.theme === <span class="code-string">'light'</span>
      ? <span class="code-string">'dark'</span> : <span class="code-string">'light'</span>
  }))
}));</code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-icon">🔌</div>
          <h3>IoC Container</h3>
          <p>Inversion of Control containers (InversifyJS, Angular's DI, Spring) manage object lifecycles and inject dependencies automatically — singletons become a <em>scope</em>, not a pattern.</p>
          <pre><code><span class="code-comment">// InversifyJS example</span>
container.<span class="code-fn">bind</span>&lt;ITheme&gt;(TYPES.Theme)
  .<span class="code-fn">to</span>(ThemeService)
  .<span class="code-fn">inSingletonScope</span>(); <span class="code-comment">// ← scope, not class</span>

<span class="code-comment">// Consumer just declares:</span>
@<span class="code-fn">inject</span>(TYPES.Theme) theme: ITheme</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="table-wrap" style="margin-top:2rem">
        <table>
          <thead>
