  <!-- ══════════ DISCUSSION ══════════ -->
  <div class="discussion">
    <h2>🔍 The Real Problem With Singletons</h2>

    <p>
      The demo above works perfectly. The theme propagates everywhere, state is consistent,
      and there's exactly one instance. So what's the problem?
      The problem is that <strong style="color:var(--text)">working and well-designed are not the same thing.</strong>
    </p>

    <h3>1. Global State Is the Root Issue</h3>
    <p>
      A Singleton is just a globally accessible object with a fancy name. Every piece of code that
      calls <code style="color:var(--accent)">ThemeManager.getInstance()</code> is implicitly depending on
      shared mutable state. That dependency is invisible — it doesn't appear in any function signature,
      constructor parameter, or interface. You can't tell from the outside that a module reaches into
      global state without reading its internals.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Testing Becomes a Nightmare</h3>
    <p>
      Because the instance persists across the lifetime of a process, unit tests bleed into each other.
      Test A toggles the theme to dark. Test B assumes it starts in light. Test B fails — but only
      when run after Test A, and only on Tuesdays when Jenkins decides to run them in alphabetical order.
      You end up writing teardown hooks to reset global state, which is a sign you've already lost.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>⚠ The Real Tell:</strong> If you find yourself writing
      <code>ThemeManager._resetForTesting()</code>, the pattern has already cost you more than it saved.
    </div>

    <h3>3. It Violates Dependency Inversion</h3>
    <p>
      Components that call <code style="color:var(--accent)">getInstance()</code> directly are hardcoded
      to a specific concrete implementation. You cannot swap in a different theme strategy, a test double,
      or a server-side-rendering-safe alternative without modifying every call site. Contrast this with
      injecting a <code style="color:var(--accent)">ThemeService</code> interface — the consumer doesn't
      care how many instances exist.
    </p>

    <h3>4. Concurrency and SSR Are Silent Killers</h3>
    <p>
      In a Node.js SSR environment, your "one instance" is shared across all incoming HTTP requests.
      User A's dark mode preference leaks into User B's server-rendered HTML. In multi-threaded
      environments the lazy initialization path has a race condition unless you add locking — at which
      point you're managing infrastructure for the privilege of having global state.
    </p>

    <h3>5. The Observer Coupling Shown Above</h3>
    <p>
      The subscriber demo illustrates a real trap. Every component that subscribes to the Singleton
      is now coupled to its event model. When the Singleton changes its notification API, every
      subscriber breaks. The Singleton becomes a God Object — it knows about everything because
      everything knows about it.
    </p>

    <div class="pro-con-grid">
      <div class="pro-box">
        <strong>✓ When Singletons Are Defensible</strong><br><br>
        <ul style="padding-left:1rem;">
          <li>Truly stateless service locators</li>
          <li>Immutable config loaded once at boot</li>
          <li>Hardware-bound resources (one GPU context)</li>
          <li>Logger — when you genuinely don't care about test isolation</li>
          <li>Small scripts with no test suite and no collaborators</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="con-box">
        <strong>✗ When You Should Refuse</strong><br><br>
        <ul style="padding-left:1rem;">
          <li>Any mutable shared state in a tested codebase</li>
          <li>SSR / multi-tenant server environments</li>
          <li>Anything a component should receive, not reach for</li>
          <li>When "one instance" is an assumption, not a hard constraint</li>
          <li>When future you might need two instances (spoiler: you will)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Better Alternatives</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">Dependency Injection</strong> — Pass the service in.
        The container manages lifetime. Components stay testable and decoupled.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">React Context / Svelte Stores / Vue provide-inject</strong> —
        Framework-native scoped state that doesn't leak across component trees or requests.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">Module-level constants</strong> — If the value is truly
        immutable, a plain ES module export is a Singleton without the ceremony or the footguns.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">Event bus with explicit subscription management</strong> —
        Decouple producers and consumers without a shared object reference.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">Zustand / Redux / Signals</strong> — Purpose-built global
        state with time-travel debugging, middleware, and test utilities built in.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>💡 The Honest Summary:</strong>
      The Singleton pattern solves a real problem — controlled access to a shared resource.
      It's overused because it's <em>easy</em>: one class, one static method, done.
      The cost is paid later, in test suites that require careful ordering, in SSR bugs that
      only appear in production, and in codebases where every module is secretly coupled to
      every other module through a chain of global state. Use it when the constraint
      "exactly one" is a hard physical or architectural requirement — not just because
      you want convenient global access.
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="footer">
    Singleton demo — one instance confirmed · Toggle the theme to see all consumers update simultaneously
  </div>

</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════
     THE SINGLETON IMPLEMENTATION
══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<script>
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  // ThemeManager Singleton
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  class ThemeManager {
    static #instance = null;

    #theme        = 'light';
    #observers    = new Map();   // name → callback
    #callCount    = 0;
    #toggleCount  = 0;

    constructor() {
      // Guard: return existing instance if somehow called directly
      if (ThemeManager.#instance) {
        return ThemeManager.#instance;
      }
      ThemeManager.#instance = this;

      // Restore persisted theme
      const saved = localStorage.getItem('singleton-theme');
      if (saved === 'dark' || saved === 'light') {
        this.#theme = saved;
      }

      this.#applyTheme();
      this.#log(`ThemeManager instantiated — theme: ${this.#theme}`);
    }

    // ── Public API ──────────────────────────────

    static getInstance() {
      if (!ThemeManager.#instance) {
        new ThemeManager();   // constructor sets #instance
      }

      // Track every call for the demo counter
      ThemeManager.#instance.#callCount++;
      ThemeManager.#instance.#updateCallUI();

      return ThemeManager.#instance;
    }

    get theme()       { return this.#theme; }
    get callCount()   { return this.#callCount; }
    get toggleCount() { return this.#toggleCount; }

    toggle() {
      this.#theme = this.#theme === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light';
      this.#toggleCount++;
      localStorage.setItem('singleton-theme', this.#theme);
      this.#applyTheme();
      this.#notifyObservers();
      this.#updateToggleUI();
      this.#log(`Theme toggled → ${this.#theme}`);
    }

    subscribe(name, callback) {
      if (this.#observers.has(name)) {
        this.#log(`Observer "${name}" already registered — skipping`);
        return false;
      }
      this.#observers.set(name, callback);
      this.#updateObserverBadge();
      this.#log(`Observer "${name}" subscribed (total: ${this.#observers.size})`);
      return true;
    }

    unsubscribe(name) {
      const removed = this.#observers.delete(name);
      if (removed) {
        this.#updateObserverBadge();
        this.#log(`Observer "${name}" unsubscribed`);
      }
      return removed;
    }

    getObserverNames() {
      return [...this.#observers.keys()];
    }

    // ── Private helpers ──────────────────────────

    #applyTheme() {
      document.body.className = this.#theme;

      const btn   = document.getElementById('themeToggle');
      const icon  = btn?.querySelector('.icon');
      const label = btn?.querySelector('.label');

      if (icon)  icon.textContent  = this.#theme === 'dark' ? '☀' : '🌙';
      if (label) label.textContent = this.#theme === 'dark' ? 'Light Mode' : 'Dark Mode';

      const alertTheme = document.getElementById('alertTheme');
      if (alertTheme) {
        alertTheme.textContent = this.#theme.toUpperCase();
        alertTheme.className   = `badge badge-${this.#theme === 'dark' ? 'warning' : 'success'}`;
      }
    }

    #notifyObservers() {
      const traceLog = document.getElementById('traceLog');
      if (!traceLog) return;

      if (this.#observers.size === 0) {
        this.#addTrace('No observers registered — notification skipped.');
        return;
      }

      this.#observers.forEach((callback, name) => {
        try {
          callback(this.#theme);
          this.#addTrace(`✓ "${name}" notified → received theme: "${this.#theme}"`);
        } catch (e) {
          this.#addTrace(`✗ "${name}" threw an error: ${e.message}`);
        }
      });
    }

    #updateCallUI() {
      const el  = document.getElementById('callCount');
      const bar = document.getElementById('callBar');
      if (el)  el.textContent = this.#callCount;
      if (bar) bar.style.width = Math.min(this.#callCount * 4, 100) + '%';
    }

    #updateToggleUI() {
      const el  = document.getElementById('toggleCount');
      const bar = document.getElementById('toggleBar');
      if (el)  el.textContent = this.#toggleCount;
      if (bar) bar.style.width = Math.min(this.#toggleCount * 10, 100) + '%';
    }

    #updateObserverBadge() {
      const badge = document.getElementById('observerBadge');
      if (badge) badge.textContent = this.#observers.size;
    }

    #log(message) {
      const container = document.getElementById('logEntries');
      if (!container) return;

      const entry = document.createElement('div');
      entry.className   = 'log-entry';
      entry.textContent = `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}] ${message}`;
      container.prepend(entry);

      // Keep log trim
      while (container.children.length > 20) {
        container.removeChild(container.lastChild);
      }
    }

    #addTrace(message) {
      const container = document.getElementById('traceLog');
      if (!container) return;

      // Remove placeholder
      const placeholder = container.querySelector('.log-entry');
      if (placeholder?.textContent.startsWith('No observers')) {
        placeholder.remove();
      }

      const entry = document.createElement('div');
      entry.className   = 'log-entry';
      entry.textContent = `[${new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}] ${message}`;
      container.prepend(entry);

      while (container.children.length > 30) {
        container.removeChild(container.lastChild);
      }
    }
  }

  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  // Observer UI helper
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  function addObserver() {
    const input = document.getElementById('subName');
    const name  = input.value.trim();
    if (!name) return;

    const tm = ThemeManager.getInstance();

    const success = tm.subscribe(name, (theme) => {
      // Each observer just logs what it received
      const item = document.getElementById(`sub-${CSS.escape(name)}`);
      if (item) {
        const dot = item.querySelector('.sub-dot');
        if (dot) {
          dot.style.background = theme === 'dark'
            ? 'var(--warning)'
            : 'var(--success)';
        }
      }
    });

    if (!success) {
      input.style.borderColor = 'var(--danger)';
      setTimeout(() => input.style.borderColor = '', 1000);
      input.value = '';
      return;
    }

    // Add to UI list
    const list = document.getElementById('subList');
    const item = document.createElement('div');
    item.className = 'sub-item';
    item.id        = `sub-${name}`;
    item.innerHTML = `
      <span><span class="sub-dot"></span>${name}</span>
      <button class="form-btn" style="padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;font-size:0.75rem;"
              onclick="removeObserver('${name}')">Remove</button>
    `;
    list.appendChild(item);

    input.value = '';
    input.style.borderColor = 'var(--success)';
    setTimeout(() => input.style.borderColor = '', 1000);
  }

  function removeObserver(name) {
    ThemeManager.getInstance().unsubscribe(name);
    const item = document.getElementById(`sub-${CSS.escape(name)}`);
    if (item) item.remove();
  }

  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  // Boot — call getInstance() from multiple
  // "modules" to prove only one instance exists
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  (function boot() {
    // Simulating three separate modules all grabbing the instance
    const tm1 = ThemeManager.getInstance(); // module: Header
    const tm2 = ThemeManager.getInstance(); // module: Sidebar
    const tm3 = ThemeManager.getInstance(); // module: Footer

    // Prove they're the same object
    console.assert(tm1 === tm2, 'FAIL: different instances!');
    console.assert(tm2 === tm3, 'FAIL: different instances!');

    document.getElementById('instanceCount').textContent = '1';

    // Auto-subscribe three built-in observers to show the coupling problem
    ['NavBar', 'Sidebar', 'Footer'].forEach(name => {
      tm1.subscribe(name, (theme) => {
        // Simulated work each component does on theme change
        void theme;
      });

      const list = document.getElementById('subList');
      const item = document.createElement('div');
      item.className = 'sub-item';
      item.id        = `sub-${name}`;
      item.innerHTML = `
        <span><span class="sub-dot"></span>${name} <em style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:0.7rem;">(built-in)</em></span>
        <button class="form-btn" style="padding:0.2rem 0.6rem;font-size:0.75rem;"
                onclick="removeObserver('${name}')">Remove</button>
      `;
      list.appendChild(item);
    });
  })();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

---

## The Discussion You Actually Wanted

### Why This Demo Lies to You (Benevolently)

The demo is clean because I **controlled every variable**. One page, one process, one user, no tests, no collaborators, no future requirements. Singletons always look elegant in demos. The damage shows up later.

---

### The Five Real Problems

**1. The Invisible Dependency Problem**

```js
// What the function signature promises:
function renderNavBar() { ... }

// What it actually does:
function renderNavBar() {
  const theme = ThemeManager.getInstance().theme; // hidden global reach
}
```

That dependency is **completely invisible** at the call site. You cannot mock it, swap it, or even know it exists without reading the body. Multiply this across 40 components and you have a codebase where nothing can be understood in isolation.

**2. Test Isolation is Structurally Broken**

```js
// Test suite order matters. This is a design smell.
beforeEach(() => {
  ThemeManager._resetInstance(); // you had to write this
});

test('defaults to light', () => { ... }); // passes alone
test('after toggle is dark', () => { ... }); // fails if run second
```

The moment you need a reset method for testing, the pattern has already imposed a maintenance tax.

**3. SSR / Multi-Tenant is a Data Leak**

In Node.js, the module cache is shared across requests. User A sets dark mode → the Singleton holds `dark` → User B's server-render gets dark mode HTML. This is a **security and correctness bug** disguised as a convenience feature.

**4. "Exactly One" Is Usually an Assumption, Not a Requirement**

> *"We'll only ever need one theme."*

Then the client asks for per-user themes. Then white-label themes. Then an admin preview mode. Now you need two instances and your entire architecture resists it.

**5. It's a God Object Magnet**

Because it's globally accessible, developers keep adding things to it. The ThemeManager starts handling themes, then user preferences, then feature flags, then analytics. It becomes the thing everything depends on and nothing can replace.

---

### The Alternatives, Honestly Ranked

| Pattern | Testable | SSR Safe | Swappable | Overhead |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Dependency Injection** | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | Medium |
| **ES Module export (immutable)** | ✅ | ✅ | ⚠ | None |
| **React Context / framework state** | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | Low |
| **Zustand / Signals** | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | Low |
| **Singleton** | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | Low |

The Singleton wins on **initial implementation speed** and loses on everything that matters at scale.

---

### When I'd Actually Use One

- A **logger** in a CLI tool with no test suite
- A **hardware resource wrapper** where the OS enforces one connection anyway  
- An **immutable config object** loaded once at process start — and even then, a plain module export is cleaner

The pattern isn't evil. It's a local optimum that becomes a global constraint.

