    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>1. Global Mutable State Is the Root Problem</h3>
      <p>
        A singleton is just a globally accessible mutable object with a fancy name.
        <code>ThemeManager.getInstance()</code> can be called from anywhere, at any time,
        and mutate shared state. This makes call-site reasoning impossible — you cannot
        look at a function signature and know what it will change. Every function that
        calls <code>getInstance()</code> has a hidden side effect.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>2. Testing Becomes a Nightmare</h3>
      <p>
        Unit tests need isolated state. A singleton carries its state across every test in
        the suite unless you manually reset it. Forgetting one <code>ThemeManager._instance = null</code>
        reset causes tests to bleed into each other. You cannot inject a mock implementation
        without monkey-patching the class itself. Dependency injection solves this completely —
        pass the manager as a constructor argument and swap it trivially in tests.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>3. It Disguises Poor Dependency Design</h3>
      <p>
        When a component deep in your tree needs the theme, the singleton lets you skip
        the architectural question of <em>how state should flow</em>. In React the honest
        answer is Context + a reducer. In Vue it is Pinia. In plain JS it is a passed-down
        event emitter. Singletons let you defer that decision forever, and the debt compounds.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>4. Server-Side Rendering Will Break You</h3>
      <p>
        In Node.js / SSR environments the module cache is shared across requests.
        A singleton holding user-specific state (theme preference, locale, session data)
        will leak between users. Request A sets <code>theme = "dark"</code>, Request B
        reads it and gets the wrong value. This is a real security and correctness bug,
        not a theoretical one.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>5. The Observer Pattern Inside Is the Useful Part</h3>
      <p>
        Notice that the valuable logic in this demo is the <code>subscribe</code> /
        <code>notify</code> system — not the singleton wrapper around it. An
        <code>EventEmitter</code> instance passed via dependency injection would give
        you identical broadcast behavior with none of the global-state downsides.
        The singleton is load-bearing only because we refused to pass the instance around.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>6. Lazy Initialization Hides Initialization Order Bugs</h3>
      <p>
        <code>getInstance()</code> creates the instance on first call. If two modules
        race to call it during startup (common in bundled apps with async chunks),
        you get non-deterministic initialization order. Explicit construction at a
        known point in your bootstrap sequence — a DI container, a React root, a
        module initializer — makes the order obvious and controllable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="analysis-point">
      <h3>7. Better Alternatives by Context</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>React/Vue/Angular:</strong> Context API, Pinia, NgRx — framework-native
        state that is scoped, testable, and SSR-safe. <br/>
        <strong>Plain JS library:</strong> Export a plain object or a factory function;
        let the consumer decide whether to share the instance. <br/>
        <strong>Node.js services:</strong> Dependency injection containers
        (<code>tsyringe</code>, <code>InversifyJS</code>) with request-scoped lifetimes. <br/>
        <strong>The one honest use-case:</strong> True process-level resources with
        real initialization cost — a DB connection pool, a logger, a config loader.
        Even then, prefer explicit DI over <code>getInstance()</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

