---

## Why Singletons Are Often Terrible — The Honest Summary

| Problem | Why It Hurts |
|---|---|
| **Global mutable state** | Anything can change it; nothing is predictable |
| **Hidden dependencies** | Function signatures lie about what they actually need |
| **Untestable by default** | Shared instance bleeds state between tests |
| **SSR / concurrency leaks** | One instance shared across all users in Node.js |
| **Tight coupling** | Refactor the singleton, grep the entire codebase |
| **Violates SRP** | The class manages logic AND its own lifecycle |

### The honest rule of thumb

> **If you reach for a singleton, ask yourself:** *"Am I doing this because it's the right design, or because I don't want to pass a parameter?"*

Nine times out of ten it's the second one. **Pass the dependency explicitly.** Your future self — and anyone who has to test your code — will thank you.
